  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States and internationally:\n\n1. In the United States:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n- Anti-Money Laundering Act of 2020\n\n2. Federal criminal statutes:\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1956 (Laundering of monetary instruments)\n- 18 U.S. Code \u00a7 1957 (Engaging in monetary transactions in property derived from specified unlawful activity)\n\n3. International frameworks:\n- Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- European Union Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n\nThese statutes typically:\n- Define money laundering\n- Establish reporting requirements\n- Mandate customer due diligence\n- Impose criminal penalties\n- Require financial institutions to implement compliance programs\n- Facilitate international cooperation in investigating and prosecuting money laundering\n\nPenalties can include significant fines, asset forfeiture, and imprisonment for individuals and organizations involved in money laundering activities.",
